In TypeScript, you can leverage type guards to enforce a known type constraint on an object property. Type guards allow you to constrain the types of expressions that follow them, ensuring that only specific types are considered true.

Here’s how you can use type guards to ensure that a property value is of a specific type, even if the type system might suggest otherwise:

```typescript
type KnownType = 'known-type';
type ExampleProperty = KnownType;

const exampleProperty: ExampleProperty = {
  someValue:'some-known-type', // This will be'some-known-type'
  anotherProperty: 42,     // This will be considered 'known-type', but TypeScript will not enforce it
};

// Using a type guard to enforce the known type
interface KnownValue {
  knownType: KnownType;
}

const knownValue: KnownValue = {
  knownType: 'known-type',
};

console.log(knownValue.someValue); // Output: 'known-type'
console.log(knownValue.anotherProperty); // Output: 42 (this will be considered 'known-type' by TypeScript)
```

In this example:
- `KnownType` is the type you know will be used.
- `ExampleProperty` is the type of the property you want to ensure has the known type.
- `KnownValue` is an interface that represents the known type.

By using the `knownType` property on `ExampleProperty`, you are explicitly defining that this property should always have the type `KnownType`, regardless of what the type system might suggest for other properties in the object.

